    <statement><p>Simplify the following expressions, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t+2}{t+2}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t+2}{2+t}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t-2}{t-2}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0003"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{t-2}{2-t}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0004"/></p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne -2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne -2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1, t\ne 2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-1, t\ne 2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}
    {\frac{t+2}{t+2}} \amp = {1, t\ne -2}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t+2</m> was crossed out, <m>-2</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne -2}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}[t]
    {\frac{t+2}{2+t}} \amp = \frac{{t+2}}{{t+2}} \\
    \amp = {1, t\ne -2}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t+2</m> was crossed out, <m>-2</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne -2}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}
    {\frac{t-2}{t-2}} \amp = {1, t\ne 2}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t-2</m> was crossed out, <m>2</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{1, t\ne 2}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{    \begin{aligned}[t]
    {\frac{t-2}{2-t}} \amp = \frac{{t-2}}{-(t-2)} \\
    \amp = \frac{1}{-1} \\
    \amp = {-1, t\ne 2}
    \end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>t-2</m> was crossed out, <m>2</m> is not in the domain. So the answer is <m>{-1, t\ne 2}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</solution>
